id="post-2760" class="post-2760 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-body-mind category-environment tag-barber tag-fashion tag-haircut tag-sustainable"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2011/02/17/sustainable-haircuts/" title="Permalink to Sustainable Haircuts" rel="bookmark">Sustainable Haircuts</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2011/02/17 12:30 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2011/02/17/sustainable-haircuts/" title="Sustainable Haircuts" rel="bookmark">2011/02/17 12:30 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>Sustainability is great and even local and small business can benefit from shifting the attitude to a more planet-friendly one. In Toronto a hair salon has started a bunch of sustainability practices at the benefits are grand!</p><blockquote><p>Over the last 17 years or so, Phillips has turned the place into something of an eco-hub, reducing the business&#8217;s electricity consumption by more than 50 percent and purging their hair and beauty product of what he considers to be environmentally harmful and personally toxic ingredients. A member of the Windshare Cooperative (co-owners of the Exhibition Place Wind Turbine with Toronto Hydro Energy Services) and the Toronto Environmental Alliance, Phillips has earned several awards for his efforts, including most recently, a Green Circle Award for Environmental Stewardship at the Mirror Awards honouring Canadian hairdressers, stylists, salons and spas. In an industry known for excess, glitzy surfaces and throw-away ideas, Phillips has tried to create a green heart at its core.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.yongestreetmedia.ca/features/worldsalon0202.aspx">Read the rest of the article.</a></p><div
